      <scopecontent id="aspace_3349d5939f2844a39b0ed8b4f2f6cc36">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Collection consists of handwritten correspondence from Gustaf Sobin to James Clifford, poetry typescripts, Sobin's annotated manuscripts, poetry chapter books, and printed ephemera. Topics covered in the collection include the lifelong friendship between Sobin and Clifford, mental health, masculinity, marriage, family life, the creative process, finances, publishing industry, editorial feedback, life in France, and travel between France and the US.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_51cfa87cd1bb030b56e00ede01e60017">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Gustaf Sobin was born November 15, 1935, in Boston, Massachusetts, and was educated at Brown University (A.B., 1958). Sobin was an American poet who made his home in Provence, France, for more than four decades up until his death. Sobin was heavily influenced by the work of his poetic peer and friend René Char. His body of work includes nearly thirty books of poetry, prose, and fiction, almost all of it reflecting his deep connection to the Provençal landscape, nature, history of the area and its geography. He married English painter Susannah Bott in 1968, with whom he had two children. Sobin died of pancreatic cancer, July 7, 2005, in Cavaillon, Vaucluse, France.</p>
         <p>"Gustaf Sobin." In Gale Literature: Contemporary Authors. Farmington Hills, MI: Gale, 2005. Gale Literature: Contemporary Authors (accessed March 1, 2024).</p>
         <p>Christopher Hawtree, "Gustaf Sobin: Four decades in Provence," The Guardian. September 26, 2005.  https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/sep/26/guardianobituaries.booksobituaries.</p>
      </bioghist>
